  "answer": "B, D) Rapid sequence or ‘crash’ induction is required in those cases where there is a high risk of vomiting and aspiration of gastric contents, eg in the non starved patient. Nausea and vomiting are complications of general anaesthesia and occur in 17% of patients. General anaesthesia is the reversible, drug induced state of unresponsiveness with analgesia and relaxation. NCEPOD (1992) reported that anaesthesia contributed to death in 1 in 1,351 cases; it was the sole cause of death in 1 in 185,000 cases.",
