  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 GA: Not just sleep, but a systemic physiological challenge.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Patients under general anaesthesia face an overall mortality rate of 0.7% and have a greater risk of pulmonary embolism compared to those under regional anaesthesia. These statistics highlight significant risks associated with general anaesthesia that clinicians must consider.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGeneral anaesthesia profoundly impacts multiple physiological systems, contributing to its inherent risks. The reported 0.7% overall mortality, though seemingly low, encompasses a spectrum of complications including cardiovascular events, respiratory failure, and adverse drug reactions. The increased risk of pulmonary embolism under general anaesthesia is multifactorial, often linked to prolonged immobility, venous stasis, and the systemic inflammatory response induced by surgery, which can be exacerbated by the depth of anaesthesia compared to regional techniques that allow for earlier mobilization and less systemic impact.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Patients under general anaesthetic are at risk of hypothermia due to impaired thermoregulation and vasodilation, not hyperthermia, especially in children.\nOption B (Incorrect): Intra-cranial pressure monitoring is required in specific neurosurgical cases, not universally for all patients undergoing general anaesthesia.\nOption C (Incorrect): Endotracheal intubation is not always required; laryngeal mask airways (LMAs) are frequently used, particularly for day-case surgeries, avoiding intubation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | General Anaesthesia | Regional Anaesthesia |\n|---|---|---|\n| Airway Management | Often requires ETT or LMA | Spontaneous breathing, no airway device |\n| Mortality Risk | Overall 0.7% (NCEPOD 1992) | Generally lower than GA |\n| PE Risk | Potentially higher due to immobility/systemic effects | Potentially lower due to earlier mobilization |\n| Temperature Regulation | Impaired, tendency to hypothermia | Less impact on core temperature |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember GA mortality and PE risk are higher than often perceived.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCEPOD (National Confidential Enquiry into Patient Outcome and Death) 1992 Report: This report highlighted the overall mortality associated with general anaesthesia as 0.7%.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | are at risk of hyperthermia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | require intra-cranial pressure monitoring in neurosurgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | require endo-tracheal intubation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | have an overall mortality of 0.7% | ✅ Correct |\n| E | are at greater risk of pulmonary embolism than those under regional anaesth | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D, E) Temperature regulation is poor in the anaesthetised patient with a tendency to hypothermia, which is** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
