  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pink discharge? Think deep, act quick, save a life!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that wound dehiscence is a critical surgical complication, often heralded by a serosanguinous discharge, and is significantly influenced by surgical technique. It carries substantial mortality, especially in the abdomen, and can lead to long-term complications like incisional hernias.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWound dehiscence represents a failure of fascial healing, typically occurring between post-operative days 5-10. The 'pink sign,' a serosanguinous discharge from the wound, is a crucial early indicator that the deeper fascial layers have separated, even if the skin remains intact. This early warning allows for prompt intervention. If the skin also separates, it results in a 'burst abdomen' with potential evisceration, a life-threatening emergency requiring immediate re-closure. If the skin remains intact, the underlying fascial defect will eventually lead to an incisional hernia, a common long-term complication. Poor surgical technique, inadequate closure, and increased intra-abdominal pressure are major contributing factors.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While NSAIDs can impair wound healing by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis, they are not considered a primary or common direct cause making wound dehiscence more frequent compared to factors like infection, poor surgical technique, or increased intra-abdominal pressure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Wound Dehiscence | Burst Abdomen | Incisional Hernia |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Definition | Separation of fascial layers | Complete separation of all abdominal wall layers with evisceration | Protrusion of tissue through a healed fascial defect |\n| Timing | Early post-op (days 5-10) | Early post-op (days 5-10) | Late post-op (months to years) |\n| Key Sign | Serosanguinous discharge ('pink sign') | Evisceration of abdominal contents | Visible bulge, pain |\n| Management | Emergency re-closure (if burst) or observation/elective repair (if contained) | Immediate surgical re-closure with tension sutures | Elective surgical repair |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: 'Pink sign' means deep layers are open; act fast to prevent a burst abdomen.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, wound dehiscence presents as a visible separation of fascial layers, often with underlying bowel or omentum visible or protruding. In cases of burst abdomen, there is complete evisceration of abdominal contents. Imaging like CT might show fascial defects or fluid collections but is usually not needed for diagnosis of overt dehiscence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Health Organization (WHO) Global Guidelines for the Prevention of Surgical Site Infection (2016/2018). These guidelines emphasize meticulous surgical technique, appropriate suture material, and management of patient risk factors to reduce surgical site complications, including dehiscence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is preceded by a serosanguinous discharge | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is commoner in patients on non steroidal anti inflammatory drugs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | is caused by poor surgical technique | ✅ Correct |\n| D | in the abdomen carries up to 46% mortality | ✅ Correct |\n| E | is complicated by incisional hernia in up to 25% | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D, E) The prevention of wound infection by antibiotics and the improvement of surgical technique has made ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
