  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Nutrition isn't static; stress and meds change the metabolic game.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies several key aspects of daily nutritional requirements in a 70 kg man, including specific electrolyte and vitamin needs, and crucial factors that significantly alter these requirements. It highlights that nutritional needs are dynamic and influenced by physiological stress and pharmacotherapy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe daily nutritional requirements for a 70 kg man are foundational knowledge in surgical and critical care. A typical adult requires approximately 70 mmol of sodium per day, which can be met by about half a liter of normal saline. Vitamin C is essential for collagen synthesis and immune function, with a daily requirement of around 50 mg. Critically, metabolic stress from conditions like head injury or other trauma significantly increases caloric and protein demands, often by 50-100% or more, due to hypermetabolism and catabolism. Furthermore, certain medications, such as aspirin, can interfere with nutrient absorption or increase metabolic turnover, thereby elevating specific nutritional needs.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The daily nitrogen requirement for a 70 kg man is approximately 14g (equivalent to about 0.2 g/kg), not 4 g/kg, which would be an excessively high and incorrect value.\nOption B (Incorrect): The daily Vitamin C requirement for an adult is around 50 mg, not 90 mg.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nutrient/Factor | Normal Daily Requirement (70kg man) | Impact of Clinical Stress/Drugs |\n|---|---|---|\n| Nitrogen | ~14 g | Increased in trauma, sepsis, burns |\n| Sodium | ~70 mmol | Increased with excessive losses, critical illness |\n| Vitamin C | ~50 mg | Increased in stress, trauma, aspirin use |\n| Head Injury | Baseline energy needs | Increased by ~61% (hypermetabolic state) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Nutritional needs are dynamic; always consider stress, trauma, and medications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable to this question, as it focuses on nutritional requirements rather than imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016) recommend tailoring nutritional support to the patient's metabolic state, which is often hypermetabolic in trauma and critical illness.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 4 g/kg of nitrogen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 90 mg of Vitamin C per day | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | half a litre of normal saline to satisfy the Na+ requirements | ✅ Correct |\n| D | increased by 61% in head injured patients | ✅ Correct |\n| E | increased by aspirin | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C, D, E) The daily nutritional requirements of a 70 kg man include 14 g of nitrogen, 70 mmol of sodium per da** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
