  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fever is a symptom, not a diagnosis; timing and context are key.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies several diverse causes of pyrexia, highlighting the broad differential required when evaluating a febrile patient. Pyrexia is a non-specific symptom that can arise from inflammatory, infectious, thrombotic, ischemic, or drug-related etiologies, particularly in the post-operative setting.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPyrexia, or fever, is a complex physiological response mediated by pyrogens that reset the hypothalamic thermoregulatory set point. Deep venous thrombosis (DVT) causes pyrexia through an inflammatory response, releasing cytokines. An anastomotic leak leads to peritonitis or abscess formation, triggering a robust systemic inflammatory response. The acute ischemic limb also induces a significant inflammatory cascade due to tissue necrosis and reperfusion injury. Phenothiazines can cause drug-induced fever, sometimes as part of neuroleptic malignant syndrome, by interfering with central thermoregulation or causing idiosyncratic reactions. Understanding these varied mechanisms is crucial for accurate diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Wound infection 24 hours after surgery. Post-operative wound infections typically manifest with pyrexia much later, usually after 3-5 days, as bacterial proliferation and inflammatory responses take time to develop. Fever within the first 24-48 hours is more commonly attributed to atelectasis, drug reactions, or blood product reactions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Timing of Post-operative Pyrexia | Common Causes |\n|---|---|\n| Immediate (<24 hours) | Atelectasis, Blood transfusion reaction, Drug fever, Malignant hyperthermia |\n| Early (24 hours - 3 days) | Atelectasis, DVT, UTI, Pneumonia, Drug fever |\n| Late (>3 days) | Wound infection, Abscess, Anastomotic leak, C. difficile colitis, Pulmonary Embolism |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For post-op fever, think '5 W's': Wind, Water, Wound, Walk, Wonder drugs.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor DVT, a duplex ultrasound of the affected limb is the diagnostic imaging of choice. For an anastomotic leak, a CT scan with oral and/or rectal contrast is often used to identify extravasation of contrast material. An acute ischemic limb would typically be evaluated with Doppler ultrasound and/or CT angiography to assess blood flow and identify the level of occlusion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) National Surgical Quality Improvement Program (NSQIP) Guidelines (Ongoing): These guidelines provide benchmarks and best practices for reducing post-operative complications, including infections and venous thromboembolism, which are common causes of pyrexia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | deep venous thrombosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | wound infection 24 hours after surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | gastro intestinal anastomotic leak | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | phenothiazines | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | the acute ishcaemic limb | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A: T, B: F, C: T, D: T, E: T) The causes of post-operative pyrexia include basal atelectasis, blood transfusion reactions, deep ve** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
