  "answer": "A: T, B: T, C: F, D: F, E: T) Complications of salivary gland surgery are reactionary haemor-rhage, especially where hypotensive anaesthesia is used. In the mastoid region the skin flap may slough. A persistent parotid duct fistula may occur or there may be a minor leak of saliva through the wound for several days post-operatively. Facial nerve damage invariably follows formal parotidectomy with recovery time in the order of 2 months, but may be as long as 2 years. Frey’s syndrome is the presence of perspiration of the cheek dur-ing a meal ( gustatory sweating ) and may follow parotidectomy. Some advocate the avulsion of the great auricular nerve and tym-panic neurectomy as a treatment for Frey’s syndrome.",
