  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Salivary surgery: mind the nerves, avoid the sweat, seal the leaks!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies common complications following salivary gland surgery, particularly parotidectomy. Great auricular nerve injury, gustatory sweating (Frey's syndrome), and cutaneous fistulae are well-documented sequelae due to the intricate anatomy of the parotid region and the nature of the surgical dissection.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSalivary gland surgery, especially parotidectomy, involves dissection in a highly neurovascular area. The great auricular nerve is often sacrificed or injured during neck incision and flap elevation, leading to neuroma formation or numbness. Gustatory sweating (Frey's syndrome) results from aberrant reinnervation of sweat glands by parasympathetic fibers intended for the salivary gland. Cutaneous fistulae can occur from persistent salivary leakage through the wound, particularly if the parotid duct or parenchyma is not adequately sealed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Contralateral gland hyperplasia is not a recognized complication of salivary gland surgery. Hyperplasia typically relates to systemic conditions or compensatory mechanisms, not a direct surgical complication.\nOption D (Incorrect): While nerve injury is a risk, the submental nerve (a sensory branch of V3) is not typically at high risk during common salivary gland surgeries like parotidectomy. The great auricular nerve and facial nerve are far more commonly implicated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication             | Mechanism                                                              | Clinical Presentation                                   | Management                                                              |\n|--------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Great Auricular Nerve Injury | Transection or traction during skin flap elevation                     | Numbness/dysesthesia of earlobe/mastoid, neuroma formation | Observation, gabapentin for pain, surgical excision for symptomatic neuroma |\n| Gustatory Sweating (Frey's Syndrome) | Aberrant reinnervation of sweat glands by parasympathetic fibers     | Sweating/flushing over parotid region during meals      | Topical antiperspirants, anticholinergics, botulinum toxin injections   |\n| Facial Nerve Injury      | Direct trauma, traction, or thermal injury during dissection           | Facial weakness/paralysis (temporary or permanent)      | Observation, physical therapy, surgical repair/reanimation for severe cases |\n| Salivary Fistula         | Incomplete sealing of salivary ducts/parenchyma, persistent leakage    | Saliva draining from wound                               | Pressure dressing, anticholinergics, re-exploration for persistent cases |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Parotidectomy risks include Frey's, facial nerve palsy, and great auricular nerve injury.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the great auricular nerve is often visualized crossing the sternocleidomastoid muscle, making it vulnerable during skin flap elevation. The facial nerve and its branches are meticulously dissected using nerve monitoring to preserve function. Salivary leaks may be evident as clear fluid during closure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery Foundation (AAO-HNSF) Clinical Practice Guideline: Salivary Gland Neoplasms (2016) recommends careful surgical technique to minimize complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | great auricular nerve neuroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | gustatory sweating | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | contralateral gland hyperplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | submental nerve neurotmesis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | cutaneous fistulae | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A: T, B: T, C: F, D: F, E: T) Complications of salivary gland surgery are reactionary haemor-rhage, especially where hypotensive a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
