  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No spleen, more platelets, more clots, and watch out for stomach holes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are B and C. Splenectomy, the surgical removal of the spleen, is associated with a thrombotic tendency due to increased platelet counts and can lead to gastric fistulae due to the spleen's close anatomical relationship with the stomach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe spleen is a significant site for platelet sequestration and destruction. Its removal leads to a transient or persistent increase in circulating platelet count (thrombocytosis or thrombocythaemia), which predisposes patients to thrombotic events. Furthermore, the short gastric vessels, which supply the fundus of the stomach, must be ligated during splenectomy. Inadvertent injury to the gastric wall during this dissection, or ischemia from aggressive ligation, can lead to necrosis and subsequent formation of a gastric fistula.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lymphocytosis is not a typical or sustained consequence of splenectomy. While the spleen is a lymphoid organ, its removal does not generally cause an increase in circulating lymphocytes.\nOption D (Incorrect): Increased osmotic fragility of red blood cells is a characteristic of conditions like hereditary spherocytosis, for which splenectomy might be performed, but it is not a complication or direct result of splenectomy itself. Splenectomy actually reduces the destruction of fragile red blood cells.\nOption E (Incorrect): Reduced Ivy time (bleeding time) indicates faster clotting. While splenectomy can cause thrombocytosis, which increases the risk of thrombosis, it does not typically lead to a reduced Ivy time, which primarily reflects platelet function and vascular integrity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Thrombocytosis | Loss of splenic platelet sequestration | Aspirin for counts >1 million, hydration |\n| Gastric fistula | Injury to short gastric vessels/stomach | NPO, drainage, surgical repair if persistent |\n| Pancreatic fistula | Injury to pancreatic tail | NPO, drainage, somatostatin analogues |\n| OPSI (Overwhelming Post-Splenectomy Infection) | Loss of splenic immune function | Vaccination, prophylactic antibiotics |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Splenectomy complications are often related to platelet regulation or anatomical proximity.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, careful dissection and ligation of the short gastric vessels along the greater curvature of the stomach are paramount to prevent gastric injury. The tail of the pancreas is also in close proximity to the splenic hilum and must be protected from trauma or thermal injury. Post-operatively, a CT scan with oral contrast might reveal extravasation if a gastric fistula is suspected.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2018 Guidelines for the management of immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) recommend splenectomy as a second-line treatment and emphasize pre-operative vaccination and post-operative monitoring for complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | lymphocytosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | thrombotic tendency | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | gastric fistulae | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | increased osmotic fragility of red blood cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | reduced Ivy time | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A: F, B: T, C: T, D: F, E: F) The complications of splenectomy include thrombocythaemia which may be treated with aspirin when gre** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
