  "answer": "A, C, D) Splenic rupture should be suspected in multiply injured patients and in particular those in whom trauma to the left upper quad- rant or left lower thorax has occurred. The patient may present shocked or become so after an initial period of recovery that may last days. Apart from the systemic signs of internal haemorrhage (pallor, tachycardia, tachypnoea, restlessness etc) the local signs include left shoulder tip pain (Kehr’s sign) which may be elicited by raising the foot of the bed and is due to referred diaphragmat- ic irritation. Less commonly (25% of cases) shifting dullness may be present in the right flank – Ballance’s sign. Splenectomy is avoided where possible due to the risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy sepsis.",
