  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Save the spleen, save a life; Kehr's sign points to the bleed.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, C, and D accurately describe key aspects of splenic rupture. Splenic injury is a common consequence of blunt abdominal trauma, and its diagnosis and management require a thorough understanding of its varied presentations and the principles of splenic preservation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenic rupture often presents with Kehr's sign, which is referred pain to the left shoulder tip due to diaphragmatic irritation from subdiaphragmatic blood. The spleen's rich vascularity means hemorrhage can be significant, but delayed presentation due to reactive hemorrhage (re-bleeding after initial tamponade) is also well-documented. Due to the critical immunological role of the spleen, especially in children, conservative management is the preferred approach whenever possible to avoid the lifelong risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy sepsis (OPSI).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Fracture of the transverse processes of the lumbar spine is not a direct or common accompaniment of splenic rupture. While both can result from trauma, they are distinct injuries and not causally linked.\nOption E (Incorrect): While intra-abdominal hemorrhage can cause shifting dullness, it is less common with splenic rupture and, if present, is typically described as Ballance's sign (fixed dullness in the left flank and shifting dullness in the right flank), not left flank shifting dullness alone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Description | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Kehr's Sign** | Left shoulder tip pain due to diaphragmatic irritation from subdiaphragmatic blood. | Classic sign of splenic rupture, indicating peritoneal irritation. |\n| **Delayed Rupture** | Initial stable period followed by sudden deterioration due to re-bleeding. | Requires high index of suspicion, especially in initially stable trauma patients. |\n| **Conservative Management** | Non-operative treatment with close monitoring. | Preferred in hemodynamically stable patients, especially children, to preserve splenic function and prevent OPSI. |\n| **OPSI** | Overwhelming post-splenectomy sepsis, a severe, life-threatening infection. | Major long-term complication of splenectomy, necessitating vaccination and patient education. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Kehr's sign, delayed rupture, and splenic preservation are hallmarks of splenic trauma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT imaging, splenic rupture appears as a laceration, hematoma (intraparenchymal or subcapsular), or active extravasation of contrast. Free fluid (blood) in the peritoneal cavity, particularly around the spleen or in the paracolic gutters, is also a key finding. Intraoperatively, a ruptured spleen will show active bleeding, capsular tears, or parenchymal disruption.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) guidelines (11th Edition, 2022) recommend non-operative management for hemodynamically stable patients with blunt splenic injury, particularly in pediatric populations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | may be associated with Kehr’s sign | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is accompanied by the fracture of the transverse processes of the lumbar sp | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | is ideally treated with conservation in infants | ✅ Correct |\n| D | may present following reactive haemorrhage | ✅ Correct |\n| E | produces left flank shifting dullness | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D) Splenic rupture should be suspected in multiply injured patients and in particular those in whom tra** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
