  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, admit for head injury; the brain is not to be trifled with.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies skull fracture and convulsion as clear indications for admission following a head injury. These findings suggest a higher risk of intracranial pathology or ongoing neurological compromise requiring inpatient observation and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA skull fracture, particularly a depressed or open fracture, indicates significant impact force and carries risks of intracranial hemorrhage, infection, and direct brain injury, necessitating admission for imaging and potential surgical intervention. Convulsions post-head injury are a critical sign of cortical irritation or underlying structural brain damage, such as contusion or hematoma, and require immediate evaluation, seizure management, and close neurological monitoring to prevent secondary brain injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Blood loss greater than 400 mls, while a significant medical concern, is not a direct indication for admission *specifically due to head injury*. It would warrant admission for hypovolemia, but not as a primary head injury criterion.\nOption D (Incorrect): Age greater than 70 years is a risk factor for worse outcomes and a lower threshold for imaging, but it is not an isolated indication for admission without other clinical signs or symptoms of head injury.\nOption E (Incorrect): Post traumatic amnesia (PTA) is a common sequela of concussion and a marker of injury severity. While concerning, isolated PTA without other neurological deficits, persistent symptoms, or high-risk features often allows for discharge with strict head injury advice, rather than mandatory admission.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication for Admission (Head Injury) | Rationale |\n|---|---|\n| Depressed/Altered Level of Consciousness | Suggests significant brain injury, requires close monitoring |\n| Skull Fracture (especially depressed/basilar) | Risk of intracranial injury, infection, CSF leak |\n| Focal Neurological Signs | Indicates specific brain region damage, requires urgent imaging |\n| Post-traumatic Seizure | Sign of cortical irritation/injury, risk of further brain damage |\n| Persistent Vomiting/Severe Headache | May indicate increased intracranial pressure or significant concussion |\n| Significant Coexisting Disorders | Complicates management, increases risk of adverse events |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Any sign of structural injury or neurological compromise warrants head injury admission.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a head CT, a skull fracture would appear as a discontinuity in the bony calvarium, potentially with associated intracranial hemorrhage (e.g., epidural, subdural, intraparenchymal) or pneumocephalus. Depressed fractures may show bone fragments driven inward.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNICE Guideline CG176 (2014, updated 2023) Head injury: assessment and early management. It recommends admission for patients with skull fracture, post-traumatic seizure, or focal neurological deficit.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | blood loss greater than 400 mls | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | skull fracture | ✅ Correct |\n| C | convulsion | ✅ Correct |\n| D | age greater than 70 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | post traumatic amnesia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C) The indications for admission to hospital following a head injury are depressed or altered level of ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
