  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Deep dermal burns: deep but not dead, still need a shot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nDeep dermal burns are correctly classified as a type of partial thickness burn, indicating that some skin elements remain viable. Due to the disruption of the skin barrier, these wounds are susceptible to infection, making tetanus prophylaxis a critical component of initial management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDeep dermal burns extend into the reticular dermis, damaging many dermal elements but crucially leaving some adnexal structures (like hair follicles and sweat glands) intact. These remaining structures provide epithelial cells for spontaneous re-epithelialization, albeit with significant scarring. The open wound created by a deep dermal burn breaches the body's primary defense against pathogens, necessitating tetanus prophylaxis to prevent a potentially fatal infection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Deep dermal burns typically retain some sensation, often to pressure, as nerve endings are not completely destroyed, though pain may be diminished compared to superficial burns. \nOption D (Incorrect): Deep dermal burns heal with scar formation due to the significant dermal damage and the need for granulation tissue. Healing by restitution implies complete regeneration without scarring. \nOption E (Incorrect): According to the Rule of Nines for adults, the entire head (including the face) represents 9% of the total body surface area, not 18% for the face alone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Depth | Appearance | Sensation | Healing | \n|---|---|---|---| \n| Superficial (1st degree) | Red, dry, painful | Intact, painful | 3-6 days, no scar | \n| Superficial Partial Thickness (2nd degree) | Blisters, moist, red, very painful | Intact, very painful | 7-21 days, minimal scar | \n| Deep Partial Thickness (2nd degree) | Waxy white/mottled red, less painful, diminished capillary refill | Diminished, pressure sensation | 3-6 weeks, significant scar | \n| Full Thickness (3rd degree) | Leathery, white/black/brown, dry, painless | Absent | Requires grafting, severe scar |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Deep dermal burns are partial thickness, painful, and prone to scarring.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo specific imaging is typically used for burn depth assessment; clinical examination is paramount. Intraoperatively, deep dermal burns may appear mottled red and white, with a waxy texture and diminished capillary refill.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (e.g., 2018). Recommends tetanus prophylaxis for all significant burns and provides detailed burn depth classification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is a partial thickness burn | ✅ Correct |\n| B | are anaesthetic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | require tetanus prophylaxis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | heal by restitution | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | of the face represent 18% surface area | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) A deep dermal burn is one that extends deeply into the dermis but enough adnexial tissue remains unh** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
