  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When bone healing stalls, look for local barriers or systemic saboteurs.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key local and systemic factors that impede the normal progression of bone healing, leading to delayed union. Delayed union signifies a fracture that has not healed within the expected timeframe for its location and type, but still retains the potential to heal.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDelayed union occurs when the biological and mechanical conditions for healing are suboptimal. Interposition of soft tissues (Option A) acts as a physical barrier, preventing direct bone-to-bone contact and callus formation. Immobilization (Option C), when either insufficient (leading to excessive motion) or excessively rigid (leading to stress shielding), disrupts the delicate balance required for osteogenesis and angiogenesis. Steroid therapy (Option E) is a systemic factor that impairs osteoblast function, reduces collagen synthesis, and can compromise the inflammatory response crucial for early healing stages, thereby prolonging the repair process.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (osteoporosis) (Incorrect): While osteoporosis is a risk factor for fracture and can complicate healing, it is not a direct cause of delayed union itself. It primarily affects bone quality and density, predisposing to fracture, rather than directly impeding the healing process once a fracture occurs.\nOption D (intensive antibiotic therapy) (Incorrect): Antibiotic therapy is used to treat infection, which can be a cause of delayed union. However, the therapy itself does not cause delayed union; rather, it aims to mitigate one of its potential causes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Factor Type | Examples | Mechanism of Impairment |\n| :---------- | :------- | :---------------------- |\n| Local       | Interposition of soft tissue, poor blood supply, infection, inadequate/excessive immobilization | Prevents bone contact, reduces nutrient/oxygen supply, inflammatory response, excessive motion |\n| Systemic    | Steroid therapy, age, nutritional status, comorbidities (e.g., diabetes, smoking) | Impairs osteoblast activity, reduces collagen synthesis, overall metabolic compromise, altered immune response |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think '3 I's and S' for delayed union: Interposition, Infection, Inadequate Immobilization, and Steroids.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs, delayed union typically presents as a persistent fracture line with minimal or no bridging callus formation at a time when significant healing should be evident. There may be evidence of sclerotic bone ends or widening of the fracture gap, but without complete non-union.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline: The Management of Open Fractures (2019) provides context on factors affecting fracture healing, including those leading to delayed union.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | interposition of soft tissues at the fracture site | ✅ Correct |\n| B | osteoporosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | immobilization | ✅ Correct |\n| D | intensive antibiotic therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | steroid therapy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, E) Delayed union is the term used to describe a bone that displays abnormal movement when the fracture ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
