  "answer": "B, D) Brachial plexus injuries are a more complex form of nerve injury but the principles of sensory, motor, autonomic reflex and trophic effects are the same. The injuries are divided into 2 groups. Upper brachial plexus injuries (Erb-Duchenne), due to displacement of the head with respect to the shoulder leads to the characteristic waiters tip position. Lower brachial plexus injuries (Klumpke) are caused by hyperextension injuries of the arm, are less common and lead to a claw-like hand. The more proximal the injury the worse the prognosis. Repair is indicated in those cases that are more distal and do not respond to conservative therapy.",
