  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 ARDS: Stiff lungs, no O2 fix, steroids *might* help.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately describes Adult Respiratory Distress Syndrome (ARDS) by identifying its historical name, a key physiological change, and a potential treatment. ARDS is a severe form of acute lung injury leading to profound respiratory failure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nARDS, formerly known as 'shock lung,' is fundamentally characterized by a significant decrease in lung compliance, meaning the lungs become stiff and difficult to inflate. This reduced elasticity is due to widespread inflammation, increased capillary permeability, and inactivation of surfactant within the alveoli, leading to pulmonary edema and alveolar collapse. The resulting severe hypoxemia is often refractory to high concentrations of supplemental oxygen. While mechanical ventilation is crucial, corticosteroids may be considered for their anti-inflammatory properties, though their role is complex and context-dependent.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): ARDS is specifically defined by hypoxemia that is *not* responsive to 100% oxygen therapy, indicating severe intrapulmonary shunting. \nOption B (Incorrect): ARDS is associated with *decreased* or inactivated surfactant, which contributes to alveolar collapse and reduced lung compliance, not excess surfactant.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | ARDS | Normal Lung |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lung Compliance | Decreased | Normal |\n| Surfactant Level | Decreased/Inactivated | Normal |\n| Oxygen Responsiveness | Poor/Refractory | Good |\n| Etiology | Sepsis, Trauma, Pancreatitis, etc. | Healthy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ARDS = Stiff lungs, no O2 response, think inflammation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nChest X-ray or CT scan typically shows bilateral diffuse infiltrates, often described as 'ground-glass opacities' or consolidation, without evidence of cardiogenic pulmonary edema. These findings reflect the widespread alveolar fluid and inflammation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe ARDS Definition Task Force (Berlin Definition) 2012. This guideline established standardized criteria for diagnosing ARDS based on timing, imaging, origin of edema, and severity of hypoxemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is manifest by hypoxaemia responsive only to 100% oxygen therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | is associated with excess surfactant | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | decreases the elasticity of the lung | ✅ Correct |\n| D | is also known as shock lung | ✅ Correct |\n| E | treatment includes steroid therapy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: C,D,E) Adult respiratory distress syndrome, formerly known as shock lung is a form of respiratory failure n** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
