  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, if they need more, they need ICU.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key indications for admission to a higher level of care, such as an Intensive Care Unit (ICU). These indications reflect the need for advanced organ support, continuous monitoring, frequent interventions, or significant nursing resources that cannot be provided in a general ward setting.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdmission to an ICU is dictated by the patient's need for specialized care beyond the scope of a general ward. This includes organ support, such as respiratory support via continuous positive pressure ventilation (CPAP) for respiratory failure, or advanced cardiac support. Invasive monitoring, like invasive arterial pressure monitoring, provides real-time physiological data crucial for managing critically ill patients. Furthermore, conditions requiring frequent medical interventions (e.g., titration of vasoactive drugs, complex fluid management) or heavy nursing requirements (e.g., frequent repositioning, complex wound care, close observation) necessitate the higher nurse-to-patient ratio and specialized skills available in an ICU.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Haemodialysis is typically performed on an outpatient basis or in a dedicated dialysis unit. While acute renal failure requiring continuous renal replacement therapy (CRRT) or haemofiltration would warrant ICU admission, standard intermittent haemodialysis itself is not an indication for ICU admission.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication for ICU Admission | Description | Example |\n| :--------------------------- | :---------- | :------ |\n| Organ Support                | Need for mechanical or pharmacological support of failing organ systems. | Mechanical ventilation, vasopressors, CRRT |\n| Invasive Monitoring          | Requirement for continuous, precise physiological data. | Invasive arterial pressure, central venous pressure, intracranial pressure |\n| Frequent Medical Intervention | Conditions requiring rapid, repeated, or complex medical adjustments. | Titration of multiple vasoactive agents, frequent neurological assessments |\n| Heavy Nursing Requirement    | Need for high nurse-to-patient ratio for observation, care, or complex procedures. | Frequent turning for pressure injury prevention, complex wound care, post-operative recovery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ICU admission is for organ support, invasive monitoring, frequent intervention, or heavy nursing.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable to this conceptual question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety of Critical Care Medicine (SCCM) Guidelines for ICU Admission, Discharge, and Triage (e.g., 2016). These guidelines provide recommendations for appropriate patient selection for ICU admission based on severity of illness, need for organ support, and monitoring capabilities.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | haemodialysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | frequent medical intervention | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | continuous positive pressure ventilation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | invasive arterial pressure monitoring | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | heavy nursing requirement | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A:F, B:T, C:T, D:T, E:T) The indications for admission to an intensive care unit may be summarised into 4 groups: organ suppo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
