  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When kidneys fail, AEIOU saves the day!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies critical, life-threatening indications for renal replacement therapy (RRT), specifically severe hyperkalemia and metabolic acidosis. These conditions represent acute, unmanageable complications of renal dysfunction that necessitate immediate intervention to prevent morbidity and mortality.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSevere hyperkalemia (>6.5 mmol/L) poses an immediate threat to cardiac function, potentially leading to fatal arrhythmias. Renal support rapidly removes excess potassium from the blood, stabilizing myocardial excitability. Similarly, severe metabolic acidosis (acidaemia) can profoundly impair cellular function, reduce cardiac contractility, and cause respiratory distress. RRT effectively corrects acid-base imbalances by removing acid precursors and restoring bicarbonate levels, thereby preventing multi-organ dysfunction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Oliguria responsive to fluid challenge suggests a pre-renal cause of acute kidney injury, which typically resolves with volume repletion and does not require renal replacement therapy.\nOption D (Incorrect): A \"lemon yellow tinge\" is a classic sign of pernicious anemia, reflecting a combination of pallor and mild jaundice, and is unrelated to indications for renal support.\nOption E (Incorrect): While elevated, a creatinine level of 145 mmol/l (approximately 1.6 mg/dL) alone is not an absolute indication for renal replacement therapy; clinical context, uremic symptoms, and other electrolyte derangements are more critical.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication | Clinical Significance |\n| :--------- | :-------------------- |\n| **A**cidosis | Severe metabolic acidosis (pH < 7.1) refractory to medical therapy |\n| **E**lectrolytes | Life-threatening hyperkalemia (>6.5 mmol/L) or other severe electrolyte imbalances |\n| **I**ntoxications | Certain dialyzable drug overdoses (e.g., lithium, salicylates) |\n| **O**verload | Refractory fluid overload causing pulmonary edema or cardiac compromise |\n| **U**remia | Uremic complications (e.g., encephalopathy, pericarditis, coagulopathy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the AEIOU mnemonic for RRT indications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPatients requiring renal support often present with signs of fluid overload on chest X-ray (e.g., pulmonary edema, pleural effusions). Intraoperatively, central venous access for dialysis catheter placement is a key consideration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO 2012 Clinical Practice Guideline for Acute Kidney Injury recommends initiating RRT for life-threatening complications of AKI, including severe hyperkalemia, refractory acidosis, and fluid overload.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | potassium greater than 6.5 mmol/l | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | oliguria responsive to fluid challenge | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | acidaemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | lemon yellow tinge | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | creatinine greater than 145 mmol/l | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A:T, B:F, C:T, D:F, E:F) The indications for renal dialysis are Hyperkalaemia > 6.5 mmol/l, fluid overload, metabolic** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
