  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Nipple discharge: A symptom, not a diagnosis; always investigate its source!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions B (plasma cellular mastitis) and E (prolactinoma) are correct because both represent established causes of nipple discharge. Plasma cellular mastitis is an inflammatory condition of the breast ducts, while a prolactinoma leads to hyperprolactinemia, causing galactorrhea.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNipple discharge can stem from various etiologies, broadly categorized into physiological, inflammatory, and endocrine. Plasma cellular mastitis, a form of periductal mastitis, is an inflammatory process involving the breast ducts, often presenting with purulent or serous discharge. Prolactinomas, pituitary adenomas secreting prolactin, cause hyperprolactinemia, which stimulates the mammary glands to produce milk, resulting in galactorrhea. Understanding these distinct pathophysiological mechanisms is crucial for accurate diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (bromocriptine) (Incorrect): Bromocriptine is a dopamine agonist used to *treat* hyperprolactinemia and galactorrhea, not a cause of nipple discharge.\nOption C (puberty) (Incorrect): While hormonal changes occur during puberty, it is not a direct pathological cause of nipple discharge. Transient, non-pathological secretions can sometimes be expressed but are not considered a disease state.\nOption D (radiotherapy) (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is a treatment modality for breast cancer and can cause local tissue changes, but it does not directly cause nipple discharge.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause | Type of Discharge | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Physiological | Clear, milky, yellow, green | Bilateral, multi-ductal, non-spontaneous, expressed |\n| Prolactinoma | Milky (galactorrhea) | Bilateral, often spontaneous, associated with amenorrhea/infertility |\n| Plasma Cellular Mastitis | Purulent, serous | Inflammatory, often associated with pain, erythema, mass |\n| Duct Papilloma/Carcinoma | Serous, sanguinous (bloody) | Unilateral, single duct, spontaneous, often persistent |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral, spontaneous, bloody discharge is concerning; bilateral, milky discharge suggests endocrine etiology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor evaluation of nipple discharge, imaging typically includes mammography and ultrasound. Ductography (galactography) can be performed for single-duct discharge to visualize the ductal system. If a prolactinoma is suspected, a pituitary MRI is indicated to assess for an adenoma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer Screening and Diagnosis (2023). These guidelines provide recommendations for the workup of nipple discharge, differentiating between benign and suspicious characteristics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | bromocriptine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | plasma cellular mastitis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | puberty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | prolactinoma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, E) Breast carcinoma may present with a sero-sanguinous discharge and therefore nipple discharge is a co** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
