  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Man boobs aren't always fat; check hormones, liver, and meds!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options, liver failure, cimetidine, and senescence, represent common causes of gynecomastia. Liver failure impairs estrogen metabolism, cimetidine has anti-androgenic effects, and senescence is a physiological cause due to hormonal shifts.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGynaecomastia results from an imbalance between estrogen and androgen action at the breast tissue level. In liver failure, the liver's ability to metabolize estrogens is reduced, leading to elevated circulating estrogen levels. Cimetidine, an H2-receptor antagonist, is known to have anti-androgenic properties, blocking androgen receptors and inhibiting testosterone synthesis. Senescence, or aging, is a physiological cause where a decline in testosterone production and/or an increase in sex hormone-binding globulin (SHBG) leads to a higher estrogen-to-androgen ratio.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Cocaine is not a recognized direct cause of gynecomastia. While substance abuse can impact overall health, cocaine does not specifically induce breast glandular proliferation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Aspirin is a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) and is not associated with causing gynecomastia. Its mechanism of action does not involve hormonal pathways that lead to breast tissue growth.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Category | Examples | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Physiological | Neonatal, Pubertal, Senescence | Transient hormonal imbalance (neonatal/pubertal), altered estrogen/androgen ratio (senescence) |\n| Pathological | Liver failure, Hypogonadism, Testicular tumors | Impaired estrogen metabolism, decreased testosterone production, ectopic hormone production |\n| Pharmacological | Cimetidine, Spironolactone, Digoxin, Ketoconazole | Anti-androgenic effects, estrogenic effects, altered hormone metabolism |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think hormones, liver, and drugs when gynecomastia appears.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or mammography, true gynecomastia appears as a subareolar, flame-shaped, or triangular area of glandular tissue, distinct from diffuse fatty tissue seen in pseudogynecomastia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for Gynecomastia (2019). Recommends a thorough history and physical exam, and targeted laboratory testing to identify underlying causes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | liver failure | ✅ Correct |\n| B | cimetidine | ✅ Correct |\n| C | cocaine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | senescence | ✅ Correct |\n| E | aspirin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D) The causes of gynaecomastia are physiological (neonatal, puber-tal and senile), hypogonadism, neop** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
