  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Prognosis isn't a guess, it's a Nottingham-indexed best!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe Nottingham Prognostic Index (NPI) is a crucial tool in breast cancer management, providing a robust estimate of patient prognosis based on key pathological features. Its use helps guide adjuvant therapy decisions and patient counseling.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe NPI is calculated using tumor size, nodal status, and histological grade, which are all independent prognostic factors for invasive breast cancer. By combining these, it offers a more comprehensive and accurate prediction of long-term survival and recurrence risk than any single factor alone. This index allows for stratification of patients into different risk groups (e.g., excellent, good, moderate, poor), enabling personalized treatment strategies and improving patient outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lobular carcinoma in situ (LCIS) is not the commonest lesion found on screening; Ductal Carcinoma In Situ (DCIS) is far more frequently detected. LCIS is often an incidental finding and is considered a marker of increased risk for invasive cancer in either breast, rather than a direct precursor lesion requiring excision in the same way as DCIS.\nOption B (Incorrect): The incidence of positive axillary nodes for a 1 cm invasive breast cancer is typically higher than 4%, often ranging from 10-20% or more depending on other tumor characteristics like grade and lymphovascular invasion.\nOption C (Incorrect): Multifocal ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) is generally considered a contraindication to wide local excision (breast-conserving surgery) due to the high likelihood of positive margins and increased local recurrence risk; mastectomy is often recommended in such cases.\nOption E (Incorrect): Madden's modified radical mastectomy preserves both the pectoralis major and minor muscles. Patey's modified radical mastectomy involves the removal of the pectoralis minor muscle while preserving the pectoralis major.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Mastectomy Type | Pectoralis Major | Pectoralis Minor | Axillary Dissection | Indication |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Radical (Halsted) | Removed | Removed | Yes | Historical, rarely performed |\n| Modified Radical (Patey) | Preserved | Removed | Yes | Invasive cancer with axillary involvement |\n| Modified Radical (Madden) | Preserved | Preserved | Yes | Invasive cancer with axillary involvement |\n| Simple/Total | Preserved | Preserved | No | DCIS, prophylaxis, palliative |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Nottingham Index = Size + Nodes + Grade.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, invasive breast cancer (which the Nottingham Index applies to) often appears as a spiculated mass with architectural distortion or microcalcifications. Intraoperatively, a tumor requiring NPI assessment would be an invasive carcinoma, and the surgeon would ensure adequate margins and perform sentinel lymph node biopsy or axillary dissection as indicated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend the use of prognostic indices, including the NPI, to help guide adjuvant therapy decisions for invasive breast cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | the commonest lesion on screening is lobular carcinoma in situ | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | positive axillary nodes occur in 4% of 1 cm cancers | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | multifocal ductal carcinoma in situ is treated with wide local excision | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | the Nottingham index is a prognostic indicator | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Madden’s modified mastectomy includes division of pectoralis minor | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
