  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Comfort is king when cure is no longer an option.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key interventions focused on symptom control and comfort for terminally ill patients. Management prioritizes improving quality of life by alleviating distressing symptoms rather than pursuing curative or life-prolonging treatments.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAntiemetics (A) are crucial for managing nausea and vomiting, common and debilitating symptoms in advanced illness. Steroids (C) can reduce inflammation, improve appetite, and alleviate pain, contributing significantly to comfort. Placement of a Celestin tube (D) is a palliative measure for malignant esophageal obstruction, allowing patients to swallow and maintain some oral intake, thereby improving quality of life by addressing dysphagia. These interventions directly align with the principles of palliative care, which emphasize symptom management and patient comfort.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Nasogastric feeding is generally not indicated in terminally ill patients as it is an invasive, life-prolonging measure that can cause discomfort and does not align with comfort-focused palliative care goals. \nOption E (Incorrect): 'PAM aid' is not a recognized medical intervention or term in the context of terminal illness management. It appears to be a distractor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Intervention Type | Purpose in Terminal Illness | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| Symptom Control | Alleviate distressing symptoms, improve comfort | Antiemetics, pain medication, steroids |\n| Palliative Procedures | Address specific issues to improve quality of life | Celestin tube for dysphagia, stoma for obstruction |\n| Nutritional Support | Focus on comfort, not life prolongation | Oral intake as tolerated, avoiding invasive feeding |\n| Psychosocial Support | Address emotional, spiritual, and social needs | Counseling, spiritual care, family support |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Palliative care prioritizes comfort and quality of life over aggressive, life-prolonging interventions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPlacement of a Celestin tube for esophageal obstruction is typically guided by endoscopy and fluoroscopy to ensure correct positioning across the stricture, restoring luminal patency. Post-procedure imaging confirms placement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Palliative Care (2023) recommend comprehensive symptom management and psychosocial support as core components of care for terminally ill patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | antiemetics | ✅ Correct |\n| B | nasogastric feeding | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | steroids | ✅ Correct |\n| D | placement of a Celestin tube | ✅ Correct |\n| E | PAM aid | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D) The patient with a terminal illness has an established diagnosis of an incurable disease with a prog** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
