  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Consent is criminal, negligence is civil.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 'failure to perform to the standard set by the law' because negligence in tort law specifically addresses a breach of the duty of care owed to a patient. This breach occurs when a healthcare provider's actions fall below the accepted standard of practice, leading to harm.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNegligence is a civil wrong (tort) that requires four elements to be proven: a duty of care owed by the defendant to the plaintiff, a breach of that duty (failure to meet the standard of care), causation (the breach directly led to the injury), and damages (actual harm suffered). The standard of care is not arbitrary but is defined by what a reasonably competent body of medical opinion would consider appropriate for a practitioner in that field, including the level of information provided for informed consent.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Absence of consent, or performing a procedure without it, constitutes assault or battery, which are criminal acts, not negligence in the law of tort.\nOption C (Incorrect): Poor documentation is an evidential issue that can weaken a defense in a negligence claim, but it is not the act of negligence itself. It makes proving the standard of care was met more difficult.\nOption D (Incorrect): Battery is a criminal offense involving unwanted physical contact, distinct from the civil tort of negligence which focuses on a breach of duty of care.\nOption E (Incorrect): Unrandomised trials relate to research methodology and the strength of medical evidence, not directly to the legal definition of negligence in clinical practice.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Medico-Legal Issue | Definition | Legal Category | Key Implication |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Negligence | Failure to meet the standard of care | Civil Tort | Breach of duty leading to harm |\n| Battery/Assault | Performing treatment without consent | Criminal Act | Unlawful physical contact/threat |\n| Poor Documentation | Inadequate record-keeping | Evidential Problem | Hinders defense in litigation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Negligence is a breach of duty, not a lack of consent.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo image was provided in the question for this topic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile no single guideline is named, the standard of care is generally anchored by 'a responsible body of medical opinion,' which is a legal standard rather than a specific clinical guideline.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | absence of consent | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | failure to perform to the standard set by the law | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | poor documentation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | battery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | unrandomised trials | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: None) Performing surgery without the informed consent of the patient is deemed to be an assault or battery** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
