  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Crush injuries crush organs, not just limbs.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies renal failure, Volkmann's deformity, and adult respiratory distress syndrome as key complications of crush injuries. These arise from the systemic effects of muscle damage, local tissue ischemia, and the body's inflammatory response to severe trauma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCrush injuries cause extensive muscle necrosis, leading to rhabdomyolysis and the release of myoglobin. Myoglobin is nephrotoxic, causing acute tubular necrosis and subsequent renal failure. Locally, sustained pressure can lead to compartment syndrome, where increased interstitial pressure compromises blood flow, resulting in muscle ischemia, fibrosis, and contractures like Volkmann's deformity. Systemically, the massive tissue injury and reperfusion can trigger a profound inflammatory response, contributing to multi-organ dysfunction, including acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) due to lung injury.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Air embolism is typically associated with vascular injury, central line insertion, or barotrauma, not a primary complication of crush injuries.\nOption E (Incorrect): While stress ulcers can occur after trauma, Curling's ulcer specifically refers to stress-induced gastric or duodenal ulcers following severe burns, not general crush injuries.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Pathophysiology | Key Clinical Feature | Management Principle |\n| :----------- | :-------------- | :------------------- | :------------------- |\n| Renal Failure | Rhabdomyolysis, myoglobinuria | Oliguria, elevated creatinine, hyperkalemia | Aggressive fluid resuscitation, urine alkalinization, dialysis |\n| Volkmann's Deformity | Untreated compartment syndrome | Fixed flexion contracture of wrist/fingers | Early fasciotomy, rehabilitation |\n| ARDS | Systemic inflammatory response, lung injury | Severe hypoxemia, bilateral infiltrates | Mechanical ventilation with lung-protective strategies |\n| Stress Ulcer (general) | Catecholamine surge, splanchnic vasoconstriction | Upper GI bleeding | PPIs, H2 blockers for prophylaxis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Crush injury triad: rhabdo-renal failure, compartment syndrome-Volkmann's, and ARDS.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging like MRI can show muscle edema and necrosis in compartment syndrome. Intraoperatively, fasciotomy is performed to relieve compartment pressure. X-rays would identify associated fractures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 10th Edition (2018) recommends early recognition and management of crush syndrome, including aggressive fluid resuscitation and monitoring for complications like renal failure and compartment syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | renal failure | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Volkmann’s deformity | ✅ Correct |\n| C | air embolism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | adult respiratory distress syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Curling’s ulcer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, D) Crush injuries are associated with regional ischaemia and muscle necrosis. This may be followed by t** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
