  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get trapped in the tunnel; know your median nerve facts!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that options A, D, and E are correct. Carpal tunnel syndrome (CTS) is a median nerve entrapment neuropathy that can be caused by systemic conditions like acromegaly, has a known rate of surgical failure, and can be initially managed with conservative measures such as diuretics.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcromegaly leads to generalized soft tissue and bone overgrowth, which can narrow the carpal tunnel and directly compress the median nerve. While carpal tunnel release surgery is highly effective, a significant minority, up to 10% of patients, may experience little to no improvement due to factors such as incomplete release, pre-existing severe nerve damage, or misdiagnosis. Diuretics are a recognized first-line conservative treatment for mild CTS symptoms, particularly when fluid retention contributes to increased pressure within the carpal tunnel, as seen in conditions like pregnancy or systemic edema.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While a Colles fracture can rarely lead to CTS due to malunion or post-traumatic swelling, it is not considered a common cause. \nOption C (Incorrect): Carpal tunnel syndrome affects the median nerve, which innervates the abductor pollicis brevis, not the abductor pollicis longus. The abductor pollicis longus is innervated by the radial nerve.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Carpal Tunnel Syndrome | De Quervain's Tenosynovitis | Cubital Tunnel Syndrome |\n| :------ | :--------------------- | :------------------------- | :---------------------- |\n| Nerve/Tendon | Median nerve | Abductor pollicis longus, Extensor pollicis brevis tendons | Ulnar nerve |\n| Location | Carpal tunnel (wrist) | First dorsal compartment (radial styloid) | Cubital tunnel (elbow) |\n| Symptoms | Numbness/tingling thumb, index, middle, radial half ring finger; thenar atrophy | Pain/swelling radial wrist, positive Finkelstein's test | Numbness/tingling ring, small finger; intrinsic muscle weakness |\n| Common Causes | Repetitive strain, pregnancy, hypothyroidism, acromegaly | Repetitive thumb/wrist movements | Repetitive elbow flexion, trauma, prolonged pressure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CTS: Median nerve, thenar atrophy, diuretics, 10% surgical failure.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, median nerve swelling and flattening within the carpal tunnel can be seen. Intraoperatively, a thickened transverse carpal ligament compressing the median nerve is the key finding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Carpal Tunnel Syndrome (e.g., 2016). It recommends non-surgical treatment first, then surgery for severe or persistent symptoms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is caused by acromegaly | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is common following Colles fracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | is associated with paresis of abductor pollicis longus in 25% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 10% have little or no improvement following surgery | ✅ Correct |\n| E | is treated with diuretics | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, D, E) Carpal tunnel syndrome may be caused by compression of the tunnel walls (eg acromegaly, rarely Colle** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
