  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Upper extremity DVT: Don't miss the 'effort' in diagnosis and treatment.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options are A, B, and C. Axillary and subclavian vein thrombosis, often termed Paget-Schroetter syndrome or Effort thrombosis, is a distinct form of upper extremity deep vein thrombosis (UEDVT) with specific etiologies and clinical presentations. Understanding its epidemiology, common presentations, and appropriate nomenclature is crucial for timely diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAxillary and subclavian vein thrombosis accounts for a small but significant percentage of all venous thromboses, often linked to repetitive overhead arm activity or central venous catheterization. The term 'Effort thrombosis' specifically refers to the primary form occurring in young, athletic individuals due to compression of the subclavian vein in the thoracic outlet, typically affecting the dominant arm (hence, more often the right). Early diagnosis is paramount as organized thrombus becomes less responsive to anticoagulation, emphasizing the need for prompt intervention to prevent post-thrombotic syndrome and pulmonary embolism.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Treatment is always indicated for symptomatic axillary and subclavian vein thrombosis, regardless of presentation time. However, the effectiveness of anticoagulation and thrombolysis significantly decreases with delayed presentation due to thrombus organization.\nOption E (Incorrect): Untreated axillary and subclavian vein thrombosis carries significant risks, including post-thrombotic syndrome (pain, swelling, functional impairment) and pulmonary embolism. Patients are rarely symptom-free at 2 weeks without treatment, and such an outcome would be highly atypical and dangerous.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Primary UEDVT (Effort Thrombosis) | Secondary UEDVT |\n|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Thoracic outlet compression (e.g., repetitive overhead activity) | Central venous catheters, malignancy, hypercoagulable states |\n| Demographics | Young, athletic individuals | Older, hospitalized, or chronically ill patients |\n| Affected Arm | Dominant arm (e.g., right) | Either arm, often related to catheter insertion site |\n| Treatment | Thrombolysis, anticoagulation, surgical decompression (thoracic outlet release) | Anticoagulation, catheter removal (if applicable), addressing underlying cause |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Effort thrombosis = dominant arm + young athlete + thoracic outlet.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuplex ultrasound is the initial diagnostic modality, showing non-compressibility and intraluminal thrombus. Venography remains the gold standard, delineating the extent of thrombosis and any underlying anatomical compression (e.g., at the thoracic outlet).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2020 Guidelines for the Management of Venous Thromboembolism: Upper Extremity Deep Vein Thrombosis recommends anticoagulation for at least 3 months and consideration of thrombolysis for acute, symptomatic primary UEDVT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | account for 2% of all venous thromboses | ✅ Correct |\n| B | affects the right hand more than the left | ✅ Correct |\n| C | is also known as Effort’s thrombosis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | treatment is required in patients who present late | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | most untreated patients are symptom free at 2 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C) The increase in incidence of axillary and subclavian vein throm-bosis is related to the use of the l** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
