  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Compressibility is the cornerstone of DVT diagnosis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A, C, and D accurately describe key aspects of venous disease investigations. Venous Doppler is a reliable, non-invasive tool for identifying proximal venous obstruction, while decreased compressibility on duplex scanning is a hallmark diagnostic feature of thrombosis. Plethysmography, a functional test, precisely measures changes in limb volume, reflecting venous hemodynamics.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVenous duplex ultrasound is the cornerstone for diagnosing deep vein thrombosis (DVT), combining B-mode imaging to visualize the vein and thrombus with Doppler flow assessment. The loss of vein wall compressibility, observed by applying pressure with the ultrasound probe, is a highly sensitive and specific sign of intraluminal thrombus. While its sensitivity decreases below the knee, Doppler remains crucial for proximal DVT. Plethysmography, by detecting changes in limb volume, provides physiological information about venous outflow obstruction and reflux, complementing anatomical imaging.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Isotopic iodine fibrinogen scanning is not the most sensitive and specific test for venous thrombosis, especially for proximal thrombi, and is rarely used clinically due to its limitations and the superiority of duplex ultrasound.\nOption E (Incorrect): Homan's sign (calf pain on dorsiflexion) is a non-specific and unreliable clinical sign for DVT, with low sensitivity and specificity, and its presence does not indicate the need for surgical thrombectomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Investigation | Principle | Key Finding for DVT | Clinical Utility |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Venous Duplex Ultrasound | B-mode imaging + Doppler flow | Loss of vein compressibility, absent/altered flow | Primary diagnostic tool for DVT, especially proximal |\n| Plethysmography | Measures limb volume changes | Reduced venous outflow, increased venous capacitance | Assesses venous hemodynamics, reflux, and obstruction |\n| Isotopic Fibrinogen Scan | Detects fibrin incorporation into thrombus | Localized uptake of isotope | Historically used, poor for proximal DVT, largely obsolete |\n| Homan's Sign | Calf pain on dorsiflexion | Subjective pain | Unreliable, non-specific clinical sign, not diagnostic |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duplex ultrasound is king for DVT; compressibility is key.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn duplex ultrasound, a thrombosed vein will appear distended, anechoic or hypoechoic, and crucially, will not fully compress with probe pressure, unlike a normal vein which completely collapses. Color Doppler will show absent or diminished flow within the thrombosed segment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines for Antithrombotic Therapy for VTE Disease (e.g., 2016). They recommend venous duplex ultrasound as the primary diagnostic test for suspected DVT.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Venous doppler reliably identifies proximal venous obstruction only | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Isotopic iodine fibrinogen scanning is the most sensitive and specific test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Decreased compressibility of the vein wall is a diagnostic feature of throm | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Plethysmography studies the change in volume of a limb | ✅ Correct |\n| E | A positive Homan’s sign indicates the need for venous thrombectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D) Venous Doppler is a cheap non invasive investigation for the investigation of proximal venous obstru** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
