  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: non-bilious vomit, palpable olive, surgical fix.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (HPS) is a common surgical condition in infants, and its incidence is a key epidemiological fact. Understanding the prevalence helps in recognizing the disease early.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypertrophic pyloric stenosis is characterized by hypertrophy and hyperplasia of the pyloric muscle, leading to gastric outlet obstruction. This condition typically presents in infants between 2 and 8 weeks of age with non-bilious projectile vomiting. The incidence of approximately 3 per 1,000 live births makes it one of the most common causes of surgical abdominal emergencies in infancy, necessitating prompt diagnosis and surgical correction via pyloromyotomy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While HPS has a familial component, stating exactly '7% of cases is familial' is a very specific and potentially inaccurate percentage for all cases. The risk is significantly higher for first-degree relatives, but a general familial incidence for all cases is often cited differently or as a range.\nOption C (Incorrect): HPS characteristically affects *first-born male* infants, with a male-to-female ratio of approximately 4:1 to 5:1. Female infants are affected less frequently.\nOption D (Incorrect): The vomiting in HPS is classically *non-bilious* because the obstruction is at the pylorus, proximal to the entry of the common bile duct into the duodenum. Bilious vomiting indicates an obstruction distal to the ampulla of Vater.\nOption E (Incorrect): Blood in the stool is not a typical presentation of HPS. The primary symptoms are projectile non-bilious vomiting and dehydration. While some gastric irritation might occur, gross blood in the stool is not a characteristic finding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis | Malrotation with Volvulus | Gastroesophageal Reflux (GER) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Vomiting Character | Non-bilious, projectile | Bilious, often sudden onset | Non-bilious, effortless regurgitation |\n| Onset | 2-8 weeks of age | First month of life, can be later | Early infancy |\n| Abdominal Exam | Palpable \"olive\" in RUQ | Distended, tender, signs of shock | Usually benign |\n| Stool | Normal | Bloody (ischemia) | Normal |\n| Treatment | Pyloromyotomy | Ladd procedure | Lifestyle, medication, fundoplication (severe) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-bilious projectile vomiting in an infant = think pyloric stenosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound is the diagnostic imaging modality of choice, revealing a thickened pyloric muscle (>3-4 mm) and an elongated pyloric channel (>14-17 mm). Intraoperatively, a hypertrophied, firm pylorus is seen, which is incised longitudinally down to the mucosa (Ramstedt pyloromyotomy).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) provides clinical guidance on the diagnosis and surgical management of hypertrophic pyloric stenosis, emphasizing ultrasound for diagnosis and pyloromyotomy as definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | occurs in 3 in every 1,000 births | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | in 7% of cases is familial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | characteristically effects first born female infants | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | bile is present in late stages of vomiting | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | blood is present in the stool | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
