  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't wait for jelly stool; reduce it or resect it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer indicates that redcurrant jelly stool is a late sign of intussusception, appearing after 24 hours, and that surgical intervention is reserved for cases where initial hydrostatic reduction fails. This accurately reflects the typical progression and management algorithm for this acute pediatric abdominal emergency.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntussusception involves the telescoping of one bowel segment into another, leading to venous congestion, edema, and eventually ischemia and necrosis. The characteristic redcurrant jelly stool is a result of sloughed mucosa mixed with blood and mucus, indicating mucosal ischemia, which takes time to develop. Initial management prioritizes non-operative reduction via hydrostatic or pneumatic enema, which is successful in a high percentage of cases. However, if this non-invasive approach fails, or if there are signs of perforation or peritonitis, surgical exploration and manual reduction or resection become necessary to prevent further complications.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Intussusception is commoner in boys, not girls.\nOption B (Incorrect): While commonest in the first year, intussusception is rare in the first month of life.\nOption C (Incorrect): An identifiable anatomical lead point is present in only about 10% of cases, not 45%.\nOption D (Correct): Redcurrant jelly stool is indeed a late sign, typically appearing after 24 hours of symptom onset due to mucosal ischemia and sloughing.\nOption E (Correct): Hydrostatic reduction is the first-line treatment; surgery is indicated for failure of reduction or recurrence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Typical Intussusception (Infants) | Intussusception with Lead Point (Older Children/Adults) |\n| :-------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Incidence**                     | Commonest in first year of life (peak 5-9 months) | Less common, can occur at any age                        |\n| **Lead Point**                    | Rarely identified (10%)                               | More frequently identified (e.g., Meckel's, polyp, tumor) |\n| **Management**                    | Hydrostatic/pneumatic enema reduction (first-line) | Often requires surgical reduction/resection              |\n| **Recurrence after reduction**    | ~5-10%                                            | Higher, especially if lead point not addressed           |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Redcurrant jelly stool is late; surgery is for failed reduction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the classic 'target sign' or 'doughnut sign' (transverse view) or 'pseudokidney sign' (longitudinal view) is seen. During hydrostatic reduction, fluoroscopy or ultrasound guides the enema. In the operating room, the invaginated bowel segment is identified, and manual reduction is attempted. If reduction is unsuccessful, or if the bowel is necrotic or perforated, resection with primary anastomosis is performed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Intussusception (2010, reaffirmed 2017) recommends ultrasound as the preferred diagnostic modality and pneumatic or hydrostatic enema as the first-line treatment for stable patients without signs of perforation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | is commoner in girls than boys | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | has its highest incidence in the first month of life | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | in 45% of cases an identifiable anatomical lead point is present | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | redcurrant jelly stool is passed after the first 24 hours of onset | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | surgery is indicated following failure of hydrostatic reduction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A:F, B:F, C:F, D:T, E:T) Intussusception is the invagination of one portion of the intestine into the lumen of an adjacent se** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
