  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gallstones are a chemical cocktail, not just cholesterol.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies several key components of gallstones, which are primarily classified by their chemical composition. Understanding these components is crucial for diagnosing and managing cholelithiasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstones are broadly categorized into cholesterol stones and pigment stones. Cholesterol stones, comprising about 90% of all gallstones, are predominantly cholesterol but also contain calcium salts, bilirubin, and proteins. Pigment stones are further divided into black pigment stones (composed mainly of calcium bilirubinate, calcium phosphate, and calcium carbonate) and brown pigment stones (containing calcium bilirubinate, calcium palmitate, and cholesterol). The correct options reflect these common constituents, highlighting the complex, multi-component nature of most gallstones.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While calcium palmitate is a known component of some gallstones, particularly brown pigment stones, calcium hydroxypalmitate is not typically listed as a primary or distinct component in the same way as the other correct options.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cystine is a component of cystine stones, which are a type of kidney stone, not gallstones. Its presence in the biliary system is not characteristic of cholelithiasis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gallstone Type | Primary Components | Prevalence | Associated Conditions |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cholesterol Stones | Cholesterol (>70%), Calcium salts, Bilirubin, Proteins | ~90% | Obesity, rapid weight loss, female sex, multiparity, certain medications |\n| Black Pigment Stones | Calcium bilirubinate, Calcium phosphate, Calcium carbonate | ~5% | Hemolytic disorders (e.g., sickle cell anemia), cirrhosis, advanced age |\n| Brown Pigment Stones | Calcium bilirubinate, Calcium palmitate, Cholesterol | ~5% | Biliary tract infection, parasitic infection, stasis (e.g., strictures) |\n| Mixed Stones | Variable, often cholesterol with pigment components | Most common | Similar to cholesterol stones, often a combination of factors |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gallstones are rarely pure; think cholesterol, bilirubin, and calcium salts.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones typically appear as echogenic foci within the gallbladder lumen, often with posterior acoustic shadowing, and are mobile with patient position changes. During cholecystectomy, stones can vary widely in size, shape, and color, from pale yellow cholesterol stones to dark, friable pigment stones.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Technical Review on the Epidemiology, Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Treatment of Gallstones (2019) recommends considering stone composition in patients with recurrent stones or specific risk factors, though surgical management remains primary for symptomatic cholelithiasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | calcium hydroxypalmitate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | protein | ✅ Correct |\n| C | calcium carbonate | ✅ Correct |\n| D | cystine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | calcium bilirubinate | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) Gallstones are classified by their composition. 90% are mixed with cholesterol as the major componen** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
