  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Short urethra, big problem; screen pregnant, save two lives!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key aspects of urinary tract infections: the epidemiological differences between sexes, the utility of diagnostic tests like the leucocyte esterase test, and the critical importance of screening and treatment for bacteriuria in pregnant women to prevent complications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe anatomical difference of a shorter urethra in women facilitates bacterial ascent and colonization, leading to a higher incidence of UTIs compared to men, thus men have a lower incidence. The leucocyte esterase test is a rapid dipstick method to detect pyuria, indicating an inflammatory response to infection. Screening pregnant women for asymptomatic bacteriuria and initiating antibiotic treatment is a cornerstone of prenatal care, significantly reducing the risk of pyelonephritis, premature delivery, and perinatal mortality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): X-ray investigation (along with ultrasound) is indicated for repeated cystitis in women, not \"only in men.\" It is also indicated for a single UTI in men.\nOption E (Incorrect): Prophylactic antibiotics are indicated in children with recurrent UTIs (more than three in 6 months), not contraindicated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Women | Men | Pregnant Women | Children |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | Higher (shorter urethra) | Lower | High risk for complications | Recurrent UTIs common |\n| Investigation for Recurrence | X-ray/US for repeated cystitis | X-ray/US for single UTI | Screened for bacteriuria | Prophylaxis for >3 UTIs/6mo |\n| Screening | Not routine | Not routine | Routine for bacteriuria | Not routine |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always screen pregnant women for bacteriuria; anatomy dictates UTI risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor recurrent UTIs, X-ray and ultrasound of the kidneys, ureters, and bladder are crucial to exclude urinary stones or upper tract abnormalities.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) 2019 Guidelines for Asymptomatic Bacteriuria: Recommends screening and treating asymptomatic bacteriuria in pregnant women.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | incidence is lower in men due to less bacterial colonisation of the bladder | ✅ Correct |\n| B | repeated cystitis requires X-ray investigation only in men | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | the leucocyte esterase test is used to detect pus cells in urine | ✅ Correct |\n| D | pregnant women are screened for bacteriuria and are treated if present | ✅ Correct |\n| E | prophylactic antibiotics are contraindicated in children | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D) Bacterial adherence to the urothelial surface is the first step in the\nprogress of a urinary tract i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
