  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 PSA velocity trumps a single number; don't ignore haematuria!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key aspects of prostatic carcinoma, including its potential presentation with haematuria, the significance of PSA velocity in diagnosis, and its increasing incidence. Understanding these facets is crucial for early detection and management of prostate cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProstatic carcinoma, while often mimicking benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) with lower urinary tract symptoms, can present with haematuria, particularly at the beginning of micturition, which is a critical symptom not to overlook. The concept of PSA velocity, specifically an increase greater than 0.75 ng/ml per year, is a more reliable indicator of potential malignancy than a single absolute PSA value, helping to differentiate cancer from benign conditions. Furthermore, the rising incidence of prostate cancer, attributed to factors like increased life expectancy and screening, underscores its growing public health importance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): A pronounced midline sulcus on digital rectal examination is typically associated with a normal prostate or benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), not prostatic carcinoma, which often causes effacement or loss of the sulcus due to induration or nodularity.\nOption E (Incorrect): While localized prostate cancer in men with a life expectancy greater than 5 years can be treated surgically, this option is too absolute. Treatment decisions are complex and often involve shared decision-making, considering active surveillance, radiation therapy, or radical prostatectomy, depending on risk stratification and patient preferences.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) | Prostatic Carcinoma | Normal Prostate | \n|---|---|---|---|\n| DRE Findings | Smooth, enlarged, elastic, often preserved sulcus | Hard, nodular, craggy, often effaced/lost sulcus | Smooth, firm, elastic, distinct sulcus | \n| PSA Velocity | Typically stable or slow, gradual increase | Increase >0.75 ng/ml/year (suggestive of cancer) | Stable, minimal change | \n| Common Presentation | Obstructive/irritative LUTS (hesitancy, weak stream, nocturia) | Obstructive/irritative LUTS, haematuria (less common), bone pain (advanced) | Asymptomatic | \n| Treatment (Localized) | Medical (alpha-blockers, 5-ARIs), TURP | Active surveillance, radical prostatectomy, radiation therapy | N/A |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PSA velocity >0.75 ng/ml/year is a strong indicator for prostate cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMultiparametric MRI (mpMRI) is increasingly used for prostate cancer detection, localization, and staging, identifying suspicious lesions (e.g., PI-RADS scores) that may warrant targeted biopsy. Intraoperatively, radical prostatectomy involves careful dissection to preserve neurovascular bundles for erectile function.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Prostate Cancer, Version 1.2024, recommend considering PSA velocity in conjunction with other factors for risk assessment and management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | presents with haematuria | ✅ Correct |\n| B | is suggested by a pronounced midline sulcus on digital rectal examination | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | is associated with a prostatic specific antigen increase greater than 0.75  | ✅ Correct |\n| D | has an incidence that is increasing by 3% a year | ✅ Correct |\n| E | localised disease in men with more than 5 years life expectancy is treated  | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D) Prostatic carcinoma may present in a fashion very similar to\nbenign prostatic hyperplasia – hesitanc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
