  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't confuse acute pain with chronic overflow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key differences and management principles for acute and chronic urinary retention. Chronic retention often presents insidiously with overflow symptoms like nocturnal enuresis, while acute retention, though rare in women, can be precipitated by factors like post-operative immobility in both sexes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic urinary retention is characterized by its insidious onset and lack of pain, often leading to overflow incontinence, such as nocturnal enuresis, as the bladder chronically overfills. In contrast, acute retention is sudden and painful. The anatomical and physiological differences in the female urethra and bladder neck make acute retention less common in women compared to men, where prostatic enlargement is a frequent cause. Post-operative immobility and pain can impair detrusor function and increase sphincter tone, leading to acute retention in susceptible individuals.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Chronic urinary retention is typically caused by outflow obstruction or detrusor underactivity, not primarily by urinary tract infection. UTIs are often a *complication* of retention due to urinary stasis.\nOption E (Incorrect): For chronic urinary retention, a suprapubic catheter is generally preferred over a urethral catheter. This is because it reduces the risk of ascending infection, avoids urethral trauma, and allows for easier trials without a catheter by simple clamping.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Urinary Retention | Chronic Urinary Retention |\n| :------------------ | :---------------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------------- |\n| Onset | Sudden, painful | Insidious, often painless |\n| Symptoms | Severe suprapubic pain, inability to void | Overflow incontinence (e.g., nocturnal enuresis), frequency |\n| Bladder volume | Moderately distended (often <1L) | Markedly distended (often >1L, up to several liters) |\n| Preferred Catheter | Urethral (initially) | Suprapubic (for long-term management) |\n| Common Causes | BPH, urethral stricture, drugs, post-op, neurological | BPH, detrusor underactivity, neurological, chronic outflow obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Chronic retention is painless overflow; acute is painful and sudden.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, urinary retention would appear as a significantly distended bladder, often with a post-void residual volume greater than 100-200 mL, or even liters in chronic cases. In the OR, a distended bladder may be palpable suprapubically.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) (2021) recommends prompt bladder decompression for acute urinary retention and discusses management options for chronic retention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | chronic retention presents with nocturnal enuresis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | chronic urinary retention is caused by urinary tract infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | acute retention is rare in women | ✅ Correct |\n| D | acute retention is caused by post-operative immobility | ✅ Correct |\n| E | urethral catheterisation is preferred to suprapubic in chronic retention | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C, D) Chronic urinary retention develops insidiously and is characterised by a lack of pain. Nocturnal enu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
