  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When kidneys fail, dialysis is the ultimate filter.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies key indications for renal dialysis, which are critical in managing acute and chronic kidney failure. Options B, C, and E correctly reflect severe fluid overload (pulmonary oedema), metabolic derangements (acidosis), and symptomatic uremia, all of which necessitate renal replacement therapy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRenal dialysis is a life-sustaining treatment that replaces the kidney's function in filtering waste products, excess fluid, and electrolytes from the blood. Pulmonary oedema due to fluid overload, severe metabolic acidosis refractory to medical management, and symptomatic uremia (often indicated by high urea levels) are direct threats to life that dialysis can mitigate by restoring fluid and electrolyte balance and removing toxins. These conditions represent acute, life-threatening complications of kidney failure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hyperkalaemia ≥5 mmol/l is not a definitive indication for dialysis. The threshold for dialysis due to hyperkalaemia is typically higher, often >6.5 mmol/l, especially if refractory to medical management or associated with ECG changes.\nOption D (Incorrect): Haemoglobin < 8g/dl indicates anaemia, which is a common complication of chronic kidney disease but not an acute indication for dialysis itself. Anaemia is usually managed with erythropoiesis-stimulating agents and iron supplementation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication | Dialysis Threshold/Condition |\n|---|---|\n| Hyperkalaemia | > 6.5 mmol/l (or refractory/symptomatic) |\n| Fluid Overload | Pulmonary Oedema (refractory to diuretics) |\n| Metabolic Acidosis | Severe, refractory (pH < 7.1, HCO3 < 10 mmol/L) |\n| Uraemia | > 50 mmol/l (or symptomatic, e.g., encephalopathy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember AEIOU for dialysis indications: Acidosis, Electrolytes, Intoxications, Overload, Uremia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor pulmonary oedema, a chest X-ray would typically show cardiomegaly, pleural effusions, and interstitial or alveolar infiltrates, indicating severe fluid overload.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO (Kidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes) Clinical Practice Guideline for Acute Kidney Injury (2012) recommends considering renal replacement therapy for life-threatening complications of AKI, including severe fluid overload, hyperkalemia, acidosis, and uremic complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | hyperkalaemia ≥5 mmol/l | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | pulmonary oedema | ✅ Correct |\n| C | metabolic acidosis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Haemoglobin < 8g/dl | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | uraemia > 50 mmol/l | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: B, C, E) The indications for renal dialysis are hyperkalaemia > 6.5 mmol/l, fluid overload, metabolic acidosi** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
