  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't reject the signs of rejection; they're your graft's cry for help!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options (A, B, C, E) accurately describe various clinical, laboratory, imaging, and pharmacological aspects of organ rejection, specifically kidney transplant rejection. These points cover diagnostic indicators and a key mechanism of immunosuppression.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOrgan rejection, particularly in kidney transplantation, is a complex immune response where the recipient's immune system recognizes the transplanted organ as foreign. This process often involves T-lymphocytes, which are activated by antigen-presenting cells. Interleukin-2 (IL-2) is a crucial cytokine that promotes T-cell proliferation and differentiation, thereby amplifying the immune response. Elevated plasma IL-2 levels (Option B) are thus a marker of ongoing immune activation. Cyclosporine (Option E) is a calcineurin inhibitor that prevents rejection by specifically inhibiting the production and release of IL-2, thereby blocking T-cell activation and proliferation. Clinically, rejection manifests with signs like proteinuria (Option A) due to glomerular damage and graft dysfunction, and ultrasound can reveal oedema (Option C) within the kidney, indicating inflammation and fluid accumulation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): Acute cellular rejection is initially treated with pulsed methylprednisolone (steroids). Anti-thymocyte globulin is reserved for steroid-resistant cases, not as a first-line treatment before steroids.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Immunosuppressant | Mechanism of Action | Clinical Use |\n| :----------------- | :------------------- | :----------- |\n| Cyclosporine       | Inhibits IL-2 release | Prevents T-cell activation |\n| Azathioprine       | Interferes with mRNA/DNA production | Inhibits lymphocyte proliferation |\n| Prednisolone       | Decreases IL-1 production | Broad anti-inflammatory, T-cell suppression |\n| Anti-thymocyte Globulin | Depletes T-lymphocytes | Steroid-resistant rejection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rejection signs are graft tenderness, pyrexia, reduced urine, proteinuria, and graft edema.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound of the transplanted kidney can reveal oedema, increased resistive indices, and potentially hydronephrosis if obstruction is present, all indicative of rejection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO Clinical Practice Guideline for the Care of Kidney Transplant Recipients (2009) recommends monitoring for signs of rejection and outlines diagnostic and treatment strategies, including the use of immunosuppressive agents.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | urinalysis shows proteinuria | ✅ Correct |\n| B | plasma IL-2 levels are raised | ✅ Correct |\n| C | ultrasound of the kidney shows oedema | ✅ Correct |\n| D | acute cellular rejection is treated with anti-thymocyte globulin before ste | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | cyclosporine prevents rejection by inhibiting IL-2 release | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, B, C, E) The clinical findings in rejection are tenderness over the graft, pyrexia, reduced urine output and ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 57046758-MCQ-MRCS.pdf**\n",
